---
import Layout from '~/layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About — RE-Library">
  <section class="container">
    <h1>About RE-Library</h1>
    <p>
      RE-Library is a community-curated knowledge base for reverse engineering.
      It exists because RE knowledge is scattered across blog posts, paid
      courses, Discord screenshots, and Twitter threads — and because AI
      assistants don't have a reliable, structured source of RE context to draw
      on.
    </p>

    <h2>How it's organised</h2>
    <p>
      Every entry is a markdown file under <code>content/</code> with a YAML
      frontmatter that gives it a category, platform, difficulty, and tags.
      Entries are written for two audiences at once: a human browsing the site,
      and an LLM reading the same content over the MCP server.
    </p>

    <h2>Two surfaces, one source</h2>
    <p>
      The same <code>content/</code> tree drives both the GitHub Pages site
      and the MCP server. The site is static HTML built by Astro + Pagefind;
      the MCP server is a Python package that fetches the raw markdown from
      this repo on demand and serves it to any MCP-compatible client
      (Claude Desktop, Cursor, Continue, etc.) over stdio.
    </p>

    <h2>DRM scope</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>drm/</code> category contains extensive technical documentation
      on CDM architectures, security levels, key-ladder theory, attestation
      flows, and historical attack patterns. By design, no specific DRM system
      is named. The content describes the systems' behaviour, security models,
      and protocol shapes — readers who know the space will recognise which
      system is being described. The repo never types the names.
    </p>
    <p>
      See <a href="https://github.com/Heretek-AI/RE-Library/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md">CONTRIBUTING.md</a>
      for the full content policy.
    </p>

    <h2>Contributing</h2>
    <p>
      New entries are welcome. The bar is "would this help the next person
      doing this work?" not "is this novel research." See CONTRIBUTING.md for
      the entry template, schema reference, and the DRM guardrail.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
